{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595916"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:08:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:08:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15379"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15379"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.14,0.17,0.07,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8070"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68555"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8070"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54012"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19590"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68555"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECoeliac disease is an autoimmune condition triggered by gluten ingestion that causes inflammation and damage to the small intestine. The genetic basis of this condition has been well-studied.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following human leukocyte antigen types is most strongly associated with coeliac disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["HLA-DQ2 or HLA-DQ8","HLA-DR3 or HLA-DR4","HLA-B27 or HLA-B51","HLA-A1 or HLA-A2","HLA-DQ4 or HLA-DQ7"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe strongest genetic association with coeliac disease is \u003Cstrong\u003EHLA-DQ2 or HLA-DQ8\u003C/strong\u003E. Approximately 95% of people with coeliac disease carry HLA-DQ2, while most of the remaining 5% carry HLA-DQ8. These HLA molecules present modified gluten peptides to T cells, initiating the autoimmune response that leads to intestinal inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHLA-DR3 or HLA-DR4\u003C/strong\u003E - These are associated with type 1 diabetes mellitus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHLA-B27 or HLA-B51\u003C/strong\u003E - B27 is associated with ankylosing spondylitis; B51 with Beh\u00e7et disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHLA-A1 or HLA-A2\u003C/strong\u003E - These are common HLA types but not specifically associated with autoimmune conditions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHLA-DQ4 or HLA-DQ7\u003C/strong\u003E - These HLA types are not specifically associated with coeliac disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of HLA-DQ2 or DQ8 is necessary but not sufficient for developing coeliac disease, as these HLA types are also found in about 30% of the general population.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Coeliac disease is strongly associated with human leukocyte antigens (HLA) DQ2 and DQ8.","Over 95% of coeliac disease patients carry HLA-DQ2, while most of the remaining patients carry HLA-DQ8.","HLA-DQ2 and DQ8 present gluten peptides to T cells, initiating the autoimmune response."],"references":["Caio G, Volta U, Sapone A, Leffler DA, De Giorgio R, Catassi C, Fasano A. Celiac disease: a comprehensive current review. BMC Med. 2019 Jul 23;17(1):142. doi: 10.1186/s12916-019-1380-z. PMID: 31331324; PMCID: PMC6647104.","Brown NK, Guandalini S, Semrad C, Kupfer SS. A Clinician\u0027s Guide to Celiac Disease HLA Genetics. Am J Gastroenterol. 2019 Oct;114(10):1587-1592. doi: 10.14309/ajg.0000000000000310. PMID: 31274511.","Espino L, N\u00fa\u00f1ez C. The HLA complex and coeliac disease. Int Rev Cell Mol Biol. 2021;358:47-83. doi: 10.1016/bs.ircmb.2020.09.009. Epub 2020 Nov 11. PMID: 33707057.","Posner EB, Haseeb M. Celiac Disease. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28722929."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54012"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15379"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54012","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54012"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T20:31:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T20:33:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8070"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68555"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null